    <language lang="en">
        <body>
            <content type="html">
                <h1>Sound correspondences of Eastern Baltic languages and lects</h1>
                    <h2>Phonology of
                Common Baltic </h2>
                    <p>The story must begin with the Common-Baltic (later CB)
                phonological inventory from which each of the languages will diverge very
                    similarly
                    and yet with differences</p>
                    <p>Let us start with consonants:
                </p>
                <table class="outside inside">
                    <caption class="center">
                        CB consonants
                    </caption>
                    <tr>
                        <td></td>
                        <td>Labials</td>
                        <td>Coronals</td>
                        <td>Dorsals</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Plosives</td>
                        <td>*p<br />*b</td>
                        <td>*t<br />*d</td>
                        <td>*k<br />*g</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Sibilants</td>
                        <td></td>
                        <td>*s (*z)<br />*š *ž</td>
                        <td></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Sonorants</td>
                        <td>*m<br />*u̯</td>
                        <td>*n<br />*r *l</td>
                        <td><br />*i̯</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                <p>
                    Then the vowel system:
                </p>
                <table
                    class="outside center width-20">
                    <caption class="center">
                        CB vowels
                    </caption>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="background-color: var(--pastel-colour-green)">ī̆</td>
                        <td colspan="3"></td>
                        <td style="background-color: var(--pastel-colour-green)">ū̆</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td></td>
                        <td style="background-color: var(--pastel-colour-green)">ē̆</td>
                        <td></td>
                        <td style="background-color: var(--pastel-colour-orange)">ō</td>
                        <td></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td colspan="2"></td>
                        <td style="background-color: var(--pastel-colour-green)">ā̆</td>
                        <td colspan="2"></td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                    <p> As
                seen in the Table 2 CB vowels, all vowels except for the *ō had long and short
                counterparts, *ō, however, was only long as the short ŏ (PIE *o, *h<sub>3</sub>o, h<sub>
                3</sub>e) merged with the short *ă. </p>
                    <p>
                    Due to the accentuation/prosody and the upcoming sound changes it’s worth
                mentioning that every member of the sonorants class could form a phonetic
                tautosyllabic diphthong:
                </p>
            </content>
            <content type="component" path="/components/baltistics/Diphthongs.js"
                params='{"caption":"CB diphthongs"}' />
            <content type="html"> The existence of diphthongs where the first member is long is
                basically limited to happen in the inflectional endings, although, the word *dōu̯bē
                (a pit) is believed to have had it in the root. In the table <i>CB
                    diphthongs</i> diphthongs in the non-green background are dubious. The cases of
                *ii̯ > *ī, *uu̯ > *ū are uncertain as it might have happened in in Pre-Common-Baltic
                times and later it probably got extended even more. </content>
            <content type="html">
                <h2>
                    Phonology of Common Eastern Baltic
                </h2>
                <p>
                    <i>To be continued</i>
                </p>
            </content>
        </body>
    </language>
